node.text:
Morning meds for a kitten with kidney disease ♥️

Ferguson is thriving on this medication routine, and the best part is that he actually enjoys it! I wanted to share this sped-up look at what meds and supplements he takes every morning (and also how he takes them) in case that is helpful or interesting to you.

I use Ferguson’s favorite treats to motivate him to participate in med time. As you can see, he knows the routine and actually looks forward to these sessions! There is no one right way to work with kittens who need this much medication, but my approach is to see what works best for him, to keep everything as positive as possible, and to make adjustments as needed.

Here is what you’re seeing in the video:
-Subcutaneous fluids (LRS) with a 25g butterfly needle
-Injectable famotidine (an antacid, commonly known as Pepcid) which can be given with fluids
-Azodyl (a probiotic supporting renal health) mixed with churu
-Porous One (a uremic toxin binder) mixed with churu
-Orbax (an antibiotic)
-Clavamox (an antibiotic)
-Aluminum hydroxide (a phosphorous binder)
-He also gets injectable Cerenia (an antiemetic) which I do during his PM meds, so you don’t see that here

Please remember every case is different and you are advised to meet with a veterinary nephrology specialist to determine the right treatment for your kitten or cat! All of the medication given in this video is given under the guidance of Ferguson’s veterinary team.

node.text:
Nothing could warm my heart more than watching Ferguson play with Spud & the Buds! Here is 4 minutes of sweet playtime footage taken just a few minutes ago.

Fergie is 12 weeks old, while Spud & the Buds are about 5 weeks old…but due to his size and fragility they match really nicely for playtime. Now that the little ones are all healthy and past a nice long quarantine period, I felt comfortable letting him interact with them, and as you can see he is loving every minute!

Sadly, Ferguson is showing some physical signs of late stage kidney failure. To be completely honest, I have cried about it a lot over the past 24 hours. But then I’ll walk in the room and see him playing like this—or see him eat a big breakfast (more than half a can today!) and the only thing I can feel is happiness and hope. In spite of all he’s going through, he has such spunk and such a strong will to live a joyful life. I admire that about him so much. ♥️

#chimpytender

UPDATE: SHE FOUND A HOME!!! ♥️ Can we all come together and help this incredible senior gal?! Skyy is 20 years old(!) but doesn’t act a day over 10. She’s loving, affectionate, and impeccably fluffy. Skyy was well-loved for her entire life, but her human recently passed away and she ended up at the humane society. She so deserves a wonderful home to live out her golden years! Will you share her video & tag friends in Southern California who might be interested in her?

Skyy is adoptable from San Diego Humane Society. Let’s boost her story & help find her an amazing home! ♥️ @sdhumanesociety

node.text:
Today we took in a new foster kitten! Spud is a tiny kitten the size & development of a 5-7 day old, but if you can believe this…he’s actually 16 days old! He was born very prematurely when his mama, a feral cat, came into our local TNR clinic @feral_cat_coalition in a trap. He was the only kitten born, and his mama was not able to care for him, so he was raised for the past two weeks by the clinic manager, @aud_everything_is_taken. Audrey reached out and asked if we had any interest in taking him on, and of course, we said HECK YES!

His former foster name was Bruno, but since we have already raised a baby Bruno, we collectively decided to name him after what he looks like most — a chonky potato. As you can see, he has an incredible appetite and a rotund belly! Audrey, you did a beautiful job getting him through his most vulnerable weeks, and I’m so happy we can help carry the baton from here to adoption.

Welcome, Spud Spudley! We love you!🥔

node.text: Does your cat know any fun tricks? Sometimes cats develop an interesting behavior on their own, which you can either reinforce or ignore depending on your desired results. 😅 When Fergie started jumping on us as a way to get to higher ground, I thought it was such a cute trick that I decided to reinforce the behavior. I have been helping him learn that tap-tap-tap means “jump on me” and now he does it all the time! I just think it’s so adorable. ♥️

node.text:
Happy one year adoptaversary to my former foster ducklings! 🐥🐥🐥

Last summer, we took in a little duckling named Billie who the animal shelter believed to be a domestic pekin duck. We found him some pekin duckling friends, Marlie and Charlie, and had a blast raising the three! But Billie was always *different.* He was smaller and seemed to be totally wild. Now that he’s grown, we know he is not a domestic duck at all — but a rare white mallard! Ah, Billie, it all makes sense now! I’ll include a funny video of me trying to catch him after pool time to show how silly and…defiant he always was. Ha ha!

Raising them was such a fun experience, and now they are living their best lives at @morningsidefarmsanctuary, who you should follow and support. Swipe to the end to see what they look like all grown up!

You can watch a fun video all about Billie & friends at bit.ly/billieduck

node.text:
Thank you for all the warm words about Coco. ♥️

If you’ve ever had a senior cat for the duration of their life, maybe you will know how I’m feeling when I say that I am in absolute awe of how much we have been through together. I think about that fateful day that I found her clinging to a tree branch, and how young and genuinely clueless I was. I think about how miraculous it is that I helped her survive at a time in my life when I knew so little and had so few resources. I think of all the people and cats she has lived with, all the life transitions she has seen me through. The old Philly punk houses, the tiny DC basement apartments, the cabin in North Carolina and the woods where she loved to walk—does she remember them, I wonder? I think about all the times she comforted me through bad relationships, mean bosses, sad days. All the people whose laps she has sat in when they come to visit, because she’s the most social and loving girl. All the things she has taught me, and how she inspired me to dedicate my life to the knowledge of kitten care so that I can teach people to do better for kittens than I ever knew how to do for her as a baby.

I wonder what on earth my life would have been like if I hadn’t found her in that tree. What if I just hadn’t looked up? Who would I have become? I look at her and see all this history, healing, and possibility that came to life because we found each other.

I think about the ways we’ve both changed, and also the ways we’ve stayed the same. One thing we have always had in common is a love of the outdoors. So today, we are celebrating not being in the hospital by going on a nice, long walk together in the California sunshine, such a beautiful place where we have both somehow, miraculously, ended up together. ☀️

node.text:
For the past few weeks Coco and I have been going through something difficult, but I haven’t felt ready to talk about it publicly. Coco is my best friend of 12+ years and she recently began to have some concerning symptoms that prompted me to take her to an internal medicine specialist. After running many tests, it was suggested that we do an endoscopic biopsy of the upper and lower GI tracts, a procedure that is done under anesthesia.

The truth is that I have quite a bit of trauma from witnessing a few deaths under anesthesia firsthand, and it was honestly a difficult decision to elect to do this procedure for Coco. I knew it was the right thing to do, so about two weeks ago I scheduled her procedure, which was yesterday. I have cried so much leading up to this appointment. She was at the hospital for 11 hours yesterday and I wept like a baby dropping her off. Andrew sweetly spent the day helping me stay as distracted as possible — we hiked, we went to a market we like, and I tried to suppress my deep fear of something going wrong.

Finally around dinner time I got the call that she was up. Relief washed over me! She is home, and now we wait for results. While I’m nervous about the future, I know that whatever happens next is already happening; now I will just have more information to guide her care. I’m so proud of her for getting through this biopsy and honestly proud of myself for not fully crumbling under the weight of my sadness.

Coco is my best friend—the first kitten I ever rescued. She changed my life and we have been through so much together. I am painfully aware now that we are entering a new chapter together, but I am committed to being fully present and brave for her.

The cool thing is that we have run so many diagnostics this month that I feel like there’s nothing I don’t know about her now! She has had an echocardiogram, radiographs, bloodwork, respiratory PCR, GI panel, fecal, urinalysis, upper GI biopsy, colonoscopy, GI ultrasound…she has an amazing team and I am so grateful. I will share what feels right to share when it feels right to share it, but I wanted to share this to celebrate that her biopsy is over. ♥️

node.text:
Leap towards the things you want in life — mouth agape, eyes focused, arms ready to grasp! ♥️

Ferguson is 20 weeks old today and continues to be an absolute light in our lives. His latest nephrology appointment gave us news that was neither particularly good or particularly bad. He still has kidney disease, and all that comes along with it. While my heart wanted him to have miraculously healed, my head knows to be grateful that he is stable for now, and that all we are doing is helping him to thrive to the greatest extent possible. No one knows how much time they have — not me, you, or Ferguson, so all we can do is celebrate when today is a good day. And today is a good day! ♥️ #leapforjoy #chimpytender

node.text:
Chucky demonstrates a behavior I call the “loose latch.” This is especially common for kittens who are 5 weeks old and in their last days of bottle feeding. They still have the emotional attachment to the bottle and want to latch, but their physical dependence on nursing is waning, so they sort of loosely imitate latching without actually consuming very much. Even so, it’s kind to give them this opportunity for comfort. 🧡
